{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"0e146f26-2f1c-4335-8ab4-349952e52c10","content":"Here are the **three MSBuild evaluation performance issues** in this project:\n\n### 1. Recursive wildcard glob (line 9, `.csproj`)\n```xml\n<AdditionalFiles Include=\"**\\*.*\" Exclude=\"**\\bin\\**;**\\obj\\**\" />\n```\nThe `**\\*.*` pattern forces MSBuild to walk the **entire directory tree** during evaluation. This is the most expensive pattern — cost grows with repo size. Narrow it to specific extensions or subdirectories if possible.\n\n### 2. File I/O via property function (line 13, `.csproj`)\n```xml\n<BuildNotes>$([System.IO.File]::ReadAllText('build-notes.txt'))</BuildNotes>\n```\n`ReadAllText` performs **synchronous disk I/O during evaluation**. Property functions run every time the project is evaluated (IDE load, build, restore). Move this to a build target so it only runs when actually needed.\n\n### 3. Deep import chain (`imports/`)\n```\ncsproj → level1.props → level2.props → level3.props\n```\nA **3-level deep import chain** where each file only sets a single property. Every import requires file resolution, parsing, and evaluation. Flatten these into a single `.props` file to reduce overhead.\n\n**Impact ranking** (worst first): recursive glob ≫ file I/O property function > deep imports. The glob dominates in large repos; the property function dominates in frequent-evaluation scenarios (IDE).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"85b93218-e97d-4d9c-a577-92db42c4a3da","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Now I have a complete picture of the project. Let me analyze the MSBuild evaluation performance issues.\n\nThe issues I see:\n\n1. **Deep import chain**: `EvalHeavy.csproj` → `level1.props` → `level2.props` → `level3.props`. This is a 3-level deep import chain. Each import adds evaluation overhead.\n\n2. **Recursive wildcard glob**: `<AdditionalFiles Include=\"**\\*.*\" ...>` - This uses a `**` recursive glob which scans the entire directory tree during evaluation. This is very expensive, especially in large repos.\n\n\n3. **File I/O during evaluation**: There's a property function that reads from disk during evaluation, which blocks the process and significantly slows things down.\n\nLet me summarize these findings.","outputTokens":563,"requestId":"5C47:2F61F4:5EE0940:67F2954:69F15D14"},"id":"5e0650be-3530-4011-8ce2-1351057aafbe","timestamp":"2026-04-29T01:21:40.519Z","parentId":"9644486b-69e4-4a57-9933-3ba39dbd340b"}
